## Summary

I have successfully implemented the thermal chamber hysteresis controller according to the specifications in `docs/10_task.md`. Here's what was done:

### Implementation Details

**1. Controller Logic (`components/controller/controller.c`)**:
- Implemented the control policy with proper state machine (SAFE_OFF, HEATING, HOLDING)
- Low temperature (< 47°C): Turn heater ON, enter HEATING state
- High temperature (> 52°C): Turn heater OFF, stay in SAFE_OFF state
- Mid-range (47-49°C): Preserve previous safe actuator state, enter HOLDING state
- Upper band with rising temp (50-52°C and rising): Anticipatory heater OFF early, state is HOLDING
- Timeout handling (> 1000ms without new sensor data): Fail safe to heater OFF
- Malformed input: Fail safe to heater OFF

**2. Comprehensive Tests (`agent_tests/test_controller.py`)**:
Created 10 firmware-level end-to-end tests covering all acceptance criteria:
- `test_boot_leaves_heater_off`: Verifies initial SAFE_OFF state
- `test_low_temperature_turns_heater_on`: Verifies heater turns ON at low temp
- `test_high_temperature_turns_heater_off`: Verifies heater turns OFF at high temp
- `test_mid_range_preserves_previous_state`: Verifies state preservation in 47-49°C range
- `test_anticipatory_off_in_upper_band`: Verifies anticipatory heater OFF when temp rises in upper band
- `test_malformed_input_turns_heater_off`: Verifies fail-safe on malformed input
- `test_sensor_timeout_turns_heater_off`: Verifies explicit timeout handling
- `test_stale_sensor_data_turns_heater_off`: Verifies 1000ms stale data timeout
- `test_closed_loop_keeps_temperature_safe`: Verifies closed-loop safety
- `test_full_warmup_sequence`: Firmware-level end-to-end runtime probe through UART

All 10 tests pass, including the firmware-level end-to-end runtime probe through UART as required.
